132
00:15:46,810 --> 00:15:52,451
Our next presenter is here in person from Magnet Transport is Neema Jama.

133
00:16:03,095 --> 00:16:03,735
Hi, everyone.

134
00:16:03,755 --> 00:16:04,475
Can you hear me?

135
00:16:06,276 --> 00:16:08,538
Um, my name is Nima.

136
00:16:08,938 --> 00:16:10,960
I'm the program director for Megan Transport.

137
00:16:11,761 --> 00:16:15,964
This is our company's first CDBG City Council presentation.

138
00:16:16,585 --> 00:16:19,167
So I'll just briefly introduce our company.

139
00:16:19,187 --> 00:16:21,489
We're a small transportation company based in Medford.

140
00:16:23,871 --> 00:16:24,792
I was raised in Medford.

141
00:16:24,832 --> 00:16:25,592
Our company was

142
00:16:27,185 --> 00:16:29,206
born and built around the needs of our city.

143
00:16:30,126 --> 00:16:33,728
We have close to 30 years of transportation and delivery experience.

144
00:16:34,028 --> 00:16:37,570
We specialize in demand responsive transportation service to elders.

145
00:16:38,610 --> 00:16:47,595
We are also a minority owned business certified both by the state supplier diversity office and the city of Boston's office of economic opportunity.

146
00:16:48,223 --> 00:16:54,025
So we're applying for, as you can see on the table, two separate programs that we're proposing.

147
00:16:54,105 --> 00:17:00,848
One of them is just on the bottom of the table, you can see the recommended funding sources for applicants.

148
00:17:01,408 --> 00:17:10,671
That's an extension of the transportation service we currently provide that is currently also funded by the CDBG-CB.

149
00:17:11,272 --> 00:17:13,832
The second one is the one higher up on the list.

150
00:17:13,913 --> 00:17:17,734
It's a proposal for a new transportation pilot program based on

151
00:17:18,946 --> 00:17:25,232
and residents comments from public meetings that we were participating in last year.

152
00:17:25,252 --> 00:17:28,735
So our proposal for

153
00:17:29,527 --> 00:17:29,847
the 56,000.

154
00:17:30,067 --> 00:17:49,119
Firstly, it's the shared goal of the City of Medford and Megan Transport to aid and assist in creating an environment in our community that supports and encourages a high quality of life and a decrease in health disparity by promoting access to secure, affordable nutrition.

155
00:17:50,120 --> 00:17:55,503
Our public housing residents that lack reliable transport and who tend to be people of color,

156
00:17:56,044 --> 00:18:01,148
elderly, disabled, deserve access to reliable free shuttles to affordable grocery stores.

157
00:18:01,648 --> 00:18:08,654
The onset of the global pandemic has underscored the critical importance and the intersection between effective transportation and health outcomes.

158
00:18:09,335 --> 00:18:20,303
It has highlighted and reinforced disparities within our community, the detrimental effects of food insecurity, and what the lack of access to adequate nutrition can have on one's overall well-being.

159
00:18:20,363 --> 00:18:21,244
It's no coincidence

160
00:18:21,752 --> 00:18:44,870
that poor people, poor people of color, usually elderly or disabled with multiple comorbidities are linked to that are linked to poor nutrition have the highest COVID death rates in Medford and all over the United States, with high inflation and ever widening wealth gap the reality is the most vulnerable in our, in our community are continually forced to prioritize their own resources deciding what to use them for what to forego.

161
00:18:46,200 --> 00:18:53,087
Our company is proposing a grocery shuttle program for our residents from the eight Medford Housing Authority properties to Market Basket.

162
00:18:54,248 --> 00:18:57,932
And if we can create a partnership with the Mystic Community Market as well.

163
00:18:58,513 --> 00:19:05,580
Currently, there's no transportation program for our low income residents to access affordable grocery stores or food pantries like Market Basket.

164
00:19:06,901 --> 00:19:07,482
Our program is

165
00:19:07,892 --> 00:19:12,297
focused on preventative health by eliminating transportation as a barrier to access.

166
00:19:12,857 --> 00:19:21,206
We came up with this idea, firstly, because we do currently service seniors, and a lot of them naturally ask for rides to Market Basket.

167
00:19:22,667 --> 00:19:30,415
In addition to that, we reviewed recently the 2019 Medford Food Security

168
00:19:31,300 --> 00:19:37,741
The 87-page report is based on primarily research, but also a survey conducted throughout the city in different languages.

169
00:19:38,561 --> 00:19:42,442
The survey published hundreds of answers to questions, and it's honestly quite eye-opening.

170
00:19:42,462 --> 00:19:43,982
I recommend everyone take a look at it.

171
00:19:44,543 --> 00:19:51,624
The three main problems for getting food that the participants in the survey mentioned is cost, transportation, and time and distance to stores.

172
00:19:52,864 --> 00:19:56,045
Hundreds mentioned that Market Basket is their ideal grocery store.

173
00:19:58,857 --> 00:20:03,041
I'm looking at the report now and it's just everyone's just saying market basket.

174
00:20:03,221 --> 00:20:04,342
We need a market basket.

175
00:20:04,502 --> 00:20:05,783
The prices are too high.

176
00:20:06,484 --> 00:20:07,765
We need more access.

177
00:20:07,785 --> 00:20:09,566
We need a market basket in West Medford.

178
00:20:10,187 --> 00:20:17,553
Um, so the report, if you summarize it, a lot of people say that they just want affordable grocery and it's just hard for them to access it.

179
00:20:19,035 --> 00:20:28,778
The Greater Boston Food Bank even identified Medford as a priority city in their efforts due to the high number of households struggling with food insecurity, which is one in nine households in our city.

180
00:20:29,658 --> 00:20:32,839
So there's two terms I want to familiarize the council with and anyone who's watching.

181
00:20:34,179 --> 00:20:35,580
Term number one is food mirage.

182
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:40,441
So food mirage is a food access concept, which is kind of like a food desert.

183
00:20:40,481 --> 00:20:42,962
Food desert's like when you just don't have any grocery stores around you.

184
00:20:42,982 --> 00:20:44,642
A food mirage is

185
00:20:45,156 --> 00:20:59,484
that grocery stores are plentiful, but prices are beyond the means of low-income households, making them functionally equivalent to food deserts, in that you have to go on a long journey to obtain affordable, nutritious food, and so it effectively makes them the same.

186
00:20:59,644 --> 00:21:01,545
The second term is transport poverty.

187
00:21:02,406 --> 00:21:07,409
Affordable supermarkets that fit within the budget of our low- to moderate-income Medford residents are in neighboring cities.

188
00:21:07,549 --> 00:21:12,812
Access to those without reliable transportation can be expensive, time-consuming, multiple transports

189
00:21:13,668 --> 00:21:25,794
multiple transfers on public transport, the lack of adequate transport necessary to access general services, or the inability to pay for these transport services is called transport poverty.

190
00:21:26,414 --> 00:21:35,358
So our ultimate outcome with this program is to help reduce food insecurity by providing free transport out of our food mirage community to

191
00:21:37,303 --> 00:21:40,644
grocery stores that are a lot more affordable, like Market Basket.

192
00:21:41,944 --> 00:21:49,607
In the long term, inevitably, you'll reduce diet-related diseases, disparities, save our residents extra money each month, and lessen the burden of transport poverty.

193
00:21:49,667 --> 00:22:00,590
I can talk about, you know, how food insecurity impacts our dietary choices and ultimately the likelihood of developing obesity or chronic disease and how it's going to affect possibly future pandemics.

194
00:22:02,837 --> 00:22:10,522
